<p><b>Primo Michele Levi</b> (31 July 1919—11 April 1987) was a <a href="/wiki/Jew" title="Jew">Jewish</a>-<a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italian</a> <a href="/wiki/Chemist" title="Chemist">chemist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Holocaust_survivor" title="Holocaust survivor" class="mw-redirect">Holocaust survivor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a> of <a href="/wiki/Memoirs" title="Memoirs" class="mw-redirect">memoirs</a>, <a href="/wiki/Short_stories" title="Short stories" class="mw-redirect">short stories</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poem" title="Poem" class="mw-redirect">poems</a>, <a href="/wiki/Essay" title="Essay">essays</a> and <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novels</a>.</p>
<p>He is best known for his work on the <a href="/wiki/Holocaust" title="Holocaust" class="mw-redirect">Holocaust</a>, and in particular his account of the year he spent as a prisoner in <a href="/wiki/Auschwitz_concentration_camp" title="Auschwitz concentration camp">Auschwitz</a>, the death camp in <a href="/wiki/Nazi_Germany" title="Nazi Germany">Nazi</a>-occupied <a href="/wiki/Poland" title="Poland">Poland</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/If_This_Is_a_Man" title="If This Is a Man">If This Is a Man</a></i> (published in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> as <i>Survival in Auschwitz</i>) has been described as one of the most important works of the twentieth century.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
